{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9976,"record_hash":"sha256:4d5957a05ce346c6cd9a1980944d38c8dfb2634736b964a7822bc2fce806c784","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:44:07.114Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 80f03f\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 735\nOutput:\n- user messages for intent and corrections\n- assistant messages for decisions, plans, and final status\n- tool calls for files inspected, commands run, and tests attempted\n- tool results only when they contain outcomes, failures, diffs, or important\n  evidence\n\nThe CLI should make that possible by preserving ordered records and clear record\nkinds, not by deciding which record kinds are important.\n\n### Optional Later Tool: `search`\n\nSearch is useful, but not needed for the first handoff slice.\n\n```text\nbut agentlog search <query> [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>]\n```\n\nAdd this only after the three read tools feel insufficient on real branches.\nThe first version can be plain full-text search over redacted transcript text\nand turn metadata, returning session/turn hits that the agent can inspect with\n`timeline` and `records`.\n\n## Challenge To The Initial Approach\n\nThe core approach is right: let the next agent ask GitButler for relevant\ncontext. The parts I would push on:\n\n- \"Relevant bits\" cannot mean \"dump all related transcripts.\" The first real\n  branch already has a main session plus subagent sessions. Larger branches will\n  have far more.\n- The first command needs to orient the agent, not just list opaque session\n  keys. It should expose counts, recency, agents, models, capture kinds, and\n  highlighted turn keys.\n- The next agent should be able to distinguish main-thread work from sidecar\n  review/subagent work when that information exists. If provider metadata does\n  not expose this cleanly, the CLI should still show enough facts for the agent\n  to infer cautiously.\n- Handoff should avoid pretending related means owned. A branch can have related\n  sessions that are background review, experiments, or unrelated active\n  worktree noise.\n- We should not require GitButler app APIs for this. CLI plus `but-agentlog`\n  primitives is the right first surface.\n\n## Agent-Facing Workflow\n\nA good first workflow is deliberately small:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch>\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit N]\n```\n\nThe exact names can change, but the shape matters:\n\n1. discover related sessions for the current target\n2. inspect a compact session/turn outline\n3. hydrate only the turns that look useful\n\nThe user prompt can be simple:\n\n```text\nCheck whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n```\n\nA future skill can teach agents this sequence, but the CLI should be sensible\nwithout the skill.\n\n## Discovery Output\n\nThe discovery command should answer:\n\n- which sessions are related to this branch/review/change?\n- which turns caused that relationship?\n- how recent are they?\n- how much data would reading them cost?\n- which agent/provider/model created them?\n- are they mostly one large backfill or incremental ongoing work?\n\nMachine-readable output should include at least:\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:44:07.114Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}